  "bib_entries": {
    "153124147": {
      "title": "The rise and decline of Mancur Olson's view of the Rise and Decline of Nations",
      "abstract": "The evolution of Mancur Olson's views regarding The Rise and Decline of Nations, the second of his three main books, is examined. It expands and extends to history and to the world the arguments presented in his earlier work, The Logic of Collective Action. Although Olson never abandons the idea that the accumulation of interest groups in a democratic society can lead to its economic stagnation, how this comes about and can be overcome changes somewhat by the time of his final book, Power and Prosperity, which focuses on the problems of transition economies and proper political governance. A sign of the greater complexity of his later views emerges in his analysis of the U.S. South, presented in his 1983 presidential address to the Southern Economic Association."
    },
    "38554741": {
      "title": "The composition and interests of Russia's business lobbies: testing Olson's hypothesis of the 'encompassing organization",
      "abstract": "Why are some business lobbies less benign in their external effects than others? In The rise and decline of nations (New Haven: Yale University Press, 1982 ), Mancur Olson proposed that less-encompassing groups—i.e., those whose constituents collectively represent a relatively narrow range of interests—have a greater interest in seeking the types of subsidies, tariffs, tax loopholes, and competition-limiting regulations that, while benefiting their members, impose costs on the rest of society. By drawing on a unique pair of surveys—one targeted to managers of Russian regional lobbies, and the other addressed to managers of Russian industrial enterprises—we provide what we believe to be the most direct test of this hypothesis to date. The pattern of responses is striking. Managers of both the less encompassing lobbies and the enterprises belonging to those types of organizations display stronger preferences for narrowly targeted policy interventions. Our results, that is, strongly support Olson’s hypothesis. Copyright Springer Science+Business Media, LLC 2013"
    },
    "156319395": {
      "title": "Preference aggregation in firms and corporatist organizations: the enterprise group as a cellular encompassing organization",
      "abstract": "Mancur Olson has introduced the concept of encompassing organizations to explain variation in economic growth rates among countries. Encompassing, as opposed to narrow special interest groups promote economic growth because they \"internalize externalities.\" I modify Olson's definition of encompassing organizations herein as a result of analyzing how the structure of business firms affects the formation of public policy. The Japanese \"enterprise groups\" are my paradigmatic example of cellular encompassing organizations, analogs of which are found in a surprisingly large number of countries: bank holding companies in Germany, diversified conglomerates in Netherlands and Sweden, and trading companies in Denmark. These cellular encompassing organizations are more likely than nationwide, encompassing organizations to promote efficient economic policies. Because Olson's encompassing organizations are, in practice, Schmitter's corporatist associations, the analysis has implications for all corporatist associations. Specifically, the structure of business firms can explain the greater stability of corporatist associations in countries where both cellular and nationwide corporatist organizations exist. Stability is enhanced because of the small number of individuals running cellular encompassing organizations. Hence, these organizations are better able to overcome the free rider problem that threatens large, nationwide organizations. Overall, cellular encompassing organizations promote both efficiency in public policies and greater institutional stability."
    }
  },
